"""
MKT Historical Context Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 32–34
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-deuteronomy-32-34.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/deuteronomy.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/deuteronomy.json (MKT text)

Key historical/cultural notes for this range:
- Ch32 (Song of Moses, Ha'azinu): ANE covenantal lawsuit (rib) structure; heaven
  and earth as treaty witnesses; significant textual variants at v.8 (sons of God
  vs. sons of Israel in DSS/LXX vs. MT); shedim (v.17) identified with Canaanite
  divine beings; vv.35 and 43 cited in Rom 12:19, Heb 10:30, Rom 15:10
- Ch33 (Blessing of Moses): parallel structure to Jacob's blessing (Gen 49);
  theophanic introduction from Sinai; tribal blessings with historical/geographic
  particularity; unique Jeshurun poetry
- Ch34 (Death of Moses): post-Mosaic narrative appended to the Torah; divine burial
  unique in scripture; epitaph anchors the prophet-like-Moses expectation of 18:15
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUTERONOMY = {
  "32": {
    "1": "<p>The opening call to heaven and earth as witnesses activates one of the most important conventions of ancient Near Eastern covenant law: the <em>rib</em> (lawsuit/dispute) pattern, in which YHWH summons the cosmic witnesses to hear the indictment against his covenant people. Suzerainty treaties regularly listed cosmic powers (sun, moon, stars, mountains, rivers) as treaty witnesses who would enforce the covenant and testify to violations. Heaven and earth were the standard Israelite covenant witnesses (Deut 4:26; 31:28; Isa 1:2; Mic 6:1-2). Their invocation signals that what follows is not a song of praise but a covenantal lawsuit.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The rain and dew imagery for Moses\'s teaching draws on a widespread ANE metaphor linking divine wisdom and royal instruction to life-giving precipitation. Canaanite Baal mythology identified the storm-god with rain, and the abundance of instruction was likened to rainfall. Deuteronomy inverts the association: it is not Baal but YHWH whose teaching falls like rain, and Moses\'s words rather than prophetic oracles from the storm-god are the life-giving precipitation. The four terms (rain, dew, showers on grass, showers on plants) move from heavy to gentle, suggesting the instruction accommodates itself to its audience.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The proclamation of YHWH\'s name in a liturgical setting connects the Song to Israel\'s cultic worship. In the ancient Near East, the recitation of divine names and epithets was a formal ritual act -- not merely acknowledgment but an invocation of the deity\'s presence and power. The call to the congregation to respond with praise after Moses proclaims the name anticipates the antiphonal structure of temple worship (Ps 118; Ps 136). The Song was likely used in covenant-renewal liturgy, where Israel re-enacted its covenant commitments and remembered YHWH\'s acts.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The epithet <em>ha-tsur</em> (the Rock) for YHWH is developed extensively in this Song (vv.4, 15, 18, 30, 31) and is a significant theological contribution of the Mosaic corpus. Rock imagery for deity is attested in ANE contexts -- Mesopotamian and Canaanite texts use mountain-imagery for divine stability -- but the Israelite use is distinctive in its emphasis on YHWH\'s moral reliability (<em>emunah</em> = faithfulness) and justice. The Rock who is blameless in his ways is explicitly contrasted with Israel\'s corruption (v.5) and the enemy\'s rock (v.31): YHWH alone is the stable foundation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The vocabulary of Israel as YHWH\'s children is the covenant-relationship framework assumed throughout the Song. In suzerainty treaty logic, the vassal is sometimes described as the son of the great king -- rebellion is therefore not merely political but filial betrayal. The term <em>blemish</em> (<em>mum</em>) used here is the same term applied to sacrificial animals that disqualify them from the altar (Lev 22:20-25) -- Israel has disqualified itself as a holy people by its corruption. The phrase is deliberately shocking: the covenant people have made themselves unfit for the covenant God.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The rhetorical question <em>ha-lo hu avikha qanekha</em> (is he not your father who made you?) invokes the dual basis of YHWH\'s claim on Israel: creation and covenant. <em>Qanekha</em> (who acquired/made you) uses the same root as Eve\'s proclamation at Cain\'s birth (Gen 4:1) and possibly echoes the creator-god El Elyon as possessor of heaven and earth (Gen 14:19). The foolish-senseless pairing (<em>nabal we-lo chakham</em>) is wisdom tradition language -- the fool (nabal) is the one who denies the practical consequences of God\'s rule (cf. Ps 14:1; Nabal in 1 Sam 25).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The command to remember the ancient days and consult the elders places the Song within Israel\'s pedagogical tradition of intergenerational memory. In the ancient world, the elder was the keeper of collective memory -- oral history, legal precedent, and ancestral wisdom were transmitted through the elder network. Asking your father and elder reflects the educational structure of Israelite society where formal schooling was less common than apprenticeship-style transmission within families and tribal units. The appeal to historical memory as a ground for present obedience is a structural feature of Deuteronomy as a whole.</p>",
    "8": "<p>This verse has one of the most significant textual variants in the Pentateuch. The Masoretic Text reads <em>bene yisrael</em> (sons of Israel), but the Septuagint and the Dead Sea Scrolls fragment 4QDeut have <em>bene elohim</em> (sons of God). The Dead Sea Scrolls reading is now widely accepted as original by textual critics. The verse describes YHWH (as El Elyon) distributing the nations among divine beings at the primordial ordering of the world, while keeping Israel for himself. This cosmology, which appears also in Ps 82 and Dan 10-12, undergirds the later Second Temple belief in national patron angels and explains Paul\'s interpretation in 1 Cor 10:20 (the nations sacrifice to demons).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The contrast between YHWH\'s assignment of other nations to divine beings and his claiming of Israel as his own personal portion (<em>chelqo</em>) and inheritance (<em>nachalato</em>) is the foundation of Israel\'s election theology. In the cosmology of v.8, other nations had their own divine patrons; Israel alone had YHWH directly. This makes Israel uniquely YHWH\'s, but also uniquely accountable to him -- apostasy is not merely religious error but personal betrayal of the one who refused to delegate Israel to an intermediary. The language of Jacob as YHWH\'s <em>nachalah</em> (inheritance) appears throughout the Psalms (Ps 28:9; 33:12; 74:2; 78:71).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The desert as the place of YHWH\'s finding and sheltering Israel is a fundamental metaphor in the OT prophetic tradition. Hosea (2:14; 9:10; 11:1-4), Jeremiah (2:2-3), and Ezekiel (20:10-13) all look back to the wilderness period as the foundational moment of Israel\'s relationship with YHWH -- both the intimacy of dependence and the beginnings of rebellion. The <em>tohu</em> (formless waste, same word as in Gen 1:2) and <em>yishon</em> (howling desert) describe the wilderness as a chaos-space prior to YHWH\'s ordering care. YHWH creates a people-place from chaos.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The eagle imagery for YHWH\'s care of Israel in the wilderness has been much discussed. Eagles were known in the ancient world as attentive parents -- the image of the eagle hovering over its young and carrying them on its wings appears in Exod 19:4 as well. The maternal overtones of the imagery are significant: YHWH is the nurturing parent of the infant nation. Elsewhere in Deuteronomy YHWH is the father (v.6; 1:31); here the imagery is more maternal. The ANE background includes Egyptian depictions of the sun-god Horus as a falcon protecting pharaoh, but the Israelite image is applied to the whole people, democratizing what was a royal prerogative in Egypt.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The emphasis that YHWH alone led Israel, with no foreign god beside him, directly addresses the religious syncretism that was the perennial temptation in ancient Israel. In the ANE, major deities typically had consorts, and royal patronage was secured through complex webs of divine relationships. The Kuntillet Ajrud inscriptions (8th century BCE) mention YHWH and his Asherah, suggesting popular Israelite religion sometimes imagined a divine consort. The Song insists on YHWH\'s solitary provision: the agricultural and military blessings of vv.13-14 came from him alone, not from Baal or Asherah.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The provision of honey from the rock and oil from flinty stone describes Israel dwelling in a land of abundant blessing, including unexpected gifts from inhospitable terrain. Honey from cliffs would be wild bees building in rock crevices, common in Canaan. The catalog of provisions in vv.13-14 (honey, oil, curds, milk, fat lambs, Bashan rams, goat-kids, wheat, wine) is a comprehensive picture of agricultural abundance from every zone -- highland (honey, oil), pastoral (lambs, rams, goats, curds, milk), and agricultural (wheat, wine). Bashan was famous in the ancient world for its fat cattle and strong bulls (Ps 22:12; Amos 4:1).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Bashan bulls and the grape-harvest wine of verse 14 set the scene of fullness and prosperity that immediately precedes the apostasy of v.15 -- the blessing led to rebellion. The literary structure is deliberate: YHWH gave every good thing, and the recipient of every good thing turned against the giver. This is the pattern the prophets diagnose in Israel again and again (Hos 2:8-9; 13:6). The reference to <em>dam enav</em> (blood of the grape) connects agricultural abundance to the sacrificial language that will be inverted in v.17 (Israel offers wine to demons).</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Yeshurun</em> is a poetic name for Israel occurring only four times in the OT (32:15; 33:5, 26; and Isa 44:2). It derives from a root meaning upright/straight (<em>yashar</em>) and may be an idealized name for the people-as-YHWH-intends them. Its use here is bitterly ironic: the upright one became fat and rebellious. The fatness metaphor is not incidental -- ANE covenant texts use agricultural imagery for covenant faithfulness, and abundance leading to forgetfulness and rebellion is the recurring pattern of Deuteronomy (8:12-14; 11:16). Fat is good, but when the fat one abandons the Rock who provided the fatness, the abundance becomes an instrument of judgment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The term <em>qine</em> (they made him jealous) activates the covenant relationship language of YHWH as the divine husband/patron whose exclusive claim on Israel was violated. The jealousy of YHWH is not psychological insecurity but the covenantal demand for exclusive loyalty -- the same dynamic as a suzerain who would not permit his vassal to enter into treaty relationships with another great king. Foreign gods (<em>zarim</em>, strangers/aliens) and detestable things (<em>toevot</em>) are the standard Deuteronomic categories for all illegitimate cult. The irony is that gods who are not YHWH -- who have no power -- are capable of arousing his jealousy: the real is provoked by the unreal.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The <em>shedim</em> (demons/divine beings) named here are identified with the gods of other nations whom Israel began to worship. The word <em>shedim</em> appears only here and in Ps 106:37 in the Hebrew Bible; it is cognate with the Akkadian <em>sedu</em>, a protective divine spirit (which could be either benign or malevolent depending on context). Paul draws explicitly on this verse in 1 Cor 10:20: the sacrifices of pagans are offered to demons, not to God. The description of these beings as <em>chadashim miqqarov</em> (newly come from nearby) reflects the Deuteronomic polemic: Israel abandoned the ancient God who brought them out of Egypt for the trendy local deities of Canaan.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Rock who fathered Israel is paired with the God who gave life (<em>yecholelkha</em>, from a root meaning to writhe in labor -- birth pangs). The verse thus describes YHWH with both paternal and maternal imagery in a single line: Rock-father who fathered (<em>yeladkha</em>) and God who gave birth (<em>yecholelkha</em>). Deuteronomy consistently pairs these images (1:31: as a father carries his son; 32:11: mother eagle). The double neglect -- of Rock and God -- captures Israel\'s total abandonment of the relationship: not merely forgetting acts of provision but forgetting the God who stands behind those acts as parent.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The phrase <em>yenaes mibbane ubimbanot</em> (provoked by his sons and daughters) makes the familial metaphor explicit: Israel is YHWH\'s children, and their apostasy is filial rebellion provoking a parental response. The emotional language -- YHWH filled with contempt and fury -- is more characteristic of the prophetic literature (Isa 1:4; Jer 8:19; Ezek 16) than of later theological reflection. Deuteronomy is not afraid to describe YHWH with passion: the covenant relationship is not a coldly administrative arrangement but a living bond with emotional depth.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The divine hiding of the face (<em>hester panim</em>) is a fundamental concept in the Psalms and prophetic literature for YHWH withdrawing the assurance of his presence. In Israel\'s theological vocabulary, the face of YHWH (<em>pene YHWH</em>) represented YHWH\'s favorable attention, blessing, and protection (Num 6:24-26: the Aaronic blessing). To hide the face was to withdraw that favorable presence, leaving the individual or people exposed to the chaos that YHWH\'s presence normally held at bay. The phrase occurs 30+ times in the OT, typically in lament (Ps 44:24; 88:14) and prophetic explanation of disaster (Isa 54:8; 59:2).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The <em>lo-am</em> (not-a-people) and <em>lo-el</em> (not-a-god) symmetry in verse 21 is one of the most theologically rich verses in Deuteronomy. Israel provoked YHWH with a non-god; YHWH will provoke Israel with a non-people. The not-a-people language is picked up by Hosea (Lo-ammi, 1:9-10) and becomes a key passage in Paul\'s argument about Gentile inclusion (Rom 9:25-26; 10:19). Israel\'s apostasy opened the covenantal logic to an inverted mirror: just as Israel chose what was not God, YHWH chose what was not a people. Paul sees in this verse the anticipation of Gentile election.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fire that burns down to <em>sheol</em> (the realm of the dead) and consumes the foundations of the mountains is covenant-curse imagery drawn from the language of divine judgment. Exodus 15:7 describes YHWH consuming his enemies like fire; Deuteronomy 9:3 calls YHWH a devouring fire before Israel. The cosmic scope of the judgment -- earth, mountains, sea -- reflects the ANE language of divine warfare in which the combat of the gods reshapes the physical landscape. Ugaritic Baal texts describe Mot and Yam\'s combat in similar cosmic terms.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The metaphor of YHWH exhausting his arrows against Israel is drawn from the divine-warrior tradition. YHWH as divine warrior has a quiver of weapons: pestilence, famine, wild beasts, sword, plague. The list in vv.23-25 corresponds closely to the covenant curses of ch.28 and to the prophetic judgment speeches of Ezekiel 5:16-17 and 14:12-23 (the four sore judgments). The language of weapons stored in the divine arsenal is attested in Mesopotamian divine-warrior texts (Marduk\'s weapons against Tiamat). Israel now stands on the receiving end of weapons originally deployed against its enemies in the conquest.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The four disasters of verse 24 -- famine, fever, pestilence, wild beasts -- and the sword of verse 25 constitute YHWH\'s arsenal deployed against his own people. The wild beast motif is a covenant curse (Lev 26:22; Ezek 5:17; 14:15) that reverses the conquest blessing (Exod 23:29-30: YHWH would drive out the inhabitants gradually lest the wild beasts multiply). In covenant logic, the same divine control over the natural order that protected Israel in the conquest is now mobilized against Israel in judgment. The judgment uses the same creation powers that performed the blessing.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The comprehensive scope of the judgment in verse 25 -- sword outside, terror inside, young and old, nursing infant, grey-haired elder -- mirrors the total-population language of the conquest narratives applied to Israel itself. The city/field division of judgment corresponds to the two domains of Israelite life: the agricultural territory outside the city walls and the protected interior. The erasure of age distinctions (nursing child through the grey-haired elder) signals that the judgment is not punitive targeting of the guilty but a covenant dissolution affecting the entire covenant community.</p>",
    "26": "<p>YHWH\'s statement that he considered scattering Israel to the four winds (<em>apen peat</em>, literally I will cut them into corners) is the first hint of a theme that will recur: YHWH restrains judgment for reasons beyond Israel\'s merit. Ezekiel 20:8-9 and 36:21-23 develop this explicitly: YHWH held back judgment for the sake of his holy name among the nations. The logic is covenantal-reputational: if YHWH destroys his own people utterly, the nations conclude that YHWH either lacked power to save them or abandoned his covenant commitments. Both conclusions undermine YHWH\'s honor among the nations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The restraint of judgment for the sake of YHWH\'s reputation among the nations is theologically significant: YHWH\'s actions toward Israel are shaped not only by what Israel deserves but by what YHWH\'s character and name require in the sight of the watching nations. This is the argument Moses uses in intercession (Num 14:13-16; Exod 32:11-13) and that the prophets anticipate as the basis for restoration (Isa 48:9-11; Ezek 36:21-23). YHWH\'s honor among the nations functions as a constraint on the full execution of judgment.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The description of Israel\'s enemies as a nation without counsel or understanding is ironic: the enemies who defeated Israel are themselves foolish. This is wisdom-tradition polemic against idolatry: the nations who worship powerless gods are structurally incapable of understanding the events they are participating in. The enemy does not know that Israel\'s defeat was YHWH\'s own judgment; they attribute it to their own power (v.27) and thus compound their own guilt. The polemic against enemy foolishness prepares for the divine reversal in which YHWH turns against those same enemies.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The hypothetical of verse 29 -- if they were wise, they would understand their end -- is an address to Israel as much as to the enemies. Wisdom in the OT includes both intellectual comprehension and the practical insight to draw correct behavioral conclusions from correct theological premises. A people that truly understood the dynamics of the covenant relationship -- that YHWH\'s power, not the enemy\'s, determined the outcome of battles -- would recognize where their security lay and act accordingly. The inability to grasp this is the wisdom failure that the Song indicts.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The military arithmetic of verse 30 (one routing a thousand, two routing ten thousand) frames YHWH\'s control of the battlefield in terms recognizable to any soldier: the only explanation for such impossible odds is divine intervention or divine abandonment. In ancient warfare, small groups routing vastly larger forces was understood as a divine miracle -- the Israelite tradition is full of such accounts (Gideon\'s 300, Jonathan and his armor-bearer, David and Goliath). The verse turns this tradition against Israel: the enemies achieved their impossible victory not through their own power but because YHWH sold Israel and gave them into enemy hands.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The polemical acknowledgment that even the enemies can see the difference between their rock and YHWH is significant: the comparison of gods was a standard ANE trope in political rhetoric. Sennacherib\'s boast (Isa 36:18-20; 2 Kgs 18:33-35) that no god has delivered any nation from his hand represents the opposite claim. Deuteronomy 32 inverts it: the enemies who defeated Israel acknowledge that the god who gave Israel into their hand was mightier than the gods who gave them their own victories. This is a concession to YHWH\'s superior power within the mouth of the enemy, preparing for the moment of divine reversal.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The vine of Sodom imagery activates the foundational judgment narrative of Genesis 19. Sodom and Gomorrah were destroyed by YHWH with fire and sulfur as paradigmatic examples of divine judgment against unrepentant wickedness. To describe the enemies\' vine as coming from those fields is to mark them as already judged in principle -- their produce is the fruit of a divinely condemned territory. The poison-grapes and gall/bitterness motifs appear in the lament tradition (Jer 9:15; 23:15; Lam 3:15, 19) as descriptions of divine judgment mediated through bitter suffering.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The snake-venom and cobra-poison imagery extends the toxic-wine metaphor and connects to the serpent of the wilderness period (Num 21:6-9) -- YHWH sent poisonous serpents as judgment against Israel\'s complaining. The reversal is now complete: the enemies who were supposed to be Israel\'s tools of judgment are themselves producing lethal fruit. In prophetic literature, the cup of divine wrath is a cup of poison that the nations will be made to drink (Jer 25:15-29; Hab 2:16; Rev 14:8-10). The wine imagery from verse 32 moves from sour grapes to lethal poison.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The divine storehouse metaphor (<em>kamus ittadi, chatuom be-otserotai</em>, stored up with me, sealed in my storehouses) is used in the OT for reserved divine judgment and mercy. YHWH controls the timing of judgment -- it does not happen randomly or according to human timetables but is stored and released at the divine moment. Job 38:22-23 uses the same imagery for hail stored for times of trouble and war. The sealing suggests the judgment is fully prepared and committed to, awaiting only the appointed time. This creates a sense of inevitable, delayed divine action rather than capricious or spontaneous punishment.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Verse 35 is one of the most frequently cited passages in the NT. The phrase <em>li naqam ve-shillem</em> (vengeance belongs to me and recompense) claims exclusively divine authority over the infliction of punishment. Paul cites it in Romans 12:19 (do not take revenge, for it is written: vengeance is mine) and Hebrews 10:30 also quotes it as ground for the certainty of divine judgment. The temporal language introduces the eschatological delay: the day of judgment is certain but not immediate, which is both warning and consolation -- warning to the presumptuous, consolation to those who wait on divine justice.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The turn from judgment to vindication in verse 36 marks the pivot point of the Song. <em>Yadin YHWH ammo</em> (YHWH will judge his people) is deliberately ambiguous: judgment can mean punishment or vindication depending on the context. Here the context is vindication: YHWH sees his servants exhausted and helpless, and the judicial act is in their favor. The Psalms often use this ambiguity (Ps 7:8; 26:1; 43:1) -- when the psalmist asks YHWH to judge, he means to vindicate his cause against his enemies. The transition from punishment of Israel to punishment of the enemies who presumed too much on their victory is the Song\'s climactic reversal.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The divine challenge to the enemies\' gods -- <em>ayeh eloheihem</em> (where are their gods?) -- is a standard element of ANE divine warfare rhetoric. When a nation was conquered, its gods were considered defeated or captured. Assyrian and Babylonian inscriptions describe the carrying off of enemy cult statues as proof of the gods\' defeat. The polemic question is also directed at Israel: those are the gods you sacrificed to, the rock you depended on for safety -- now let them rise and help you. The impossible challenge (gods who cannot respond) is answered in contrast by YHWH\'s presence and power in the verses that follow.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The ironic invitation to the gods to rise and help is a form of <em>reductio ad absurdum</em> applied to idolatry: if the gods are real, call on them in the moment of need. If they cannot respond, they have no real existence. This polemic runs throughout Second Isaiah (Isa 44:9-20; 45:20; 46:1-7), where the gods who were carried on carts and could not move are contrasted with YHWH who carries his people. The Elijah confrontation on Carmel (1 Kgs 18) dramatizes the same challenge: the god who answers by fire is God.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The exclusive deity declaration of verse 39 is among the clearest monotheistic statements in the Torah. <em>Re\'u ata ki ani ani hu</em> (See now that I, I am he) uses the unusual <em>ani hu</em> formulation that appears prominently in Second Isaiah (Isa 41:4; 43:10-11, 13; 46:4; 48:12) as YHWH\'s self-identification against all rivals. The four paired claims (I put to death and I bring to life; I wound and I heal) are the absolute prerogatives of deity: life and death, sickness and healing, belong to YHWH alone (contrast 2 Kgs 5:7, where the king of Israel fears he is being set up for a test of divine power over life and death).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The divine oath by the raised hand is the standard gesture for taking an oath in the ancient world: to raise the hand toward heaven was to invoke the divine witnesses to the solemnity of one\'s commitment. When YHWH raises his own hand toward heaven to swear by his own life (<em>chai anochi le-olam</em>, I live forever), it creates a uniquely self-referential oath: the eternal God swears by his own eternal existence. Hebrews 6:13-18 explicitly notes this aspect of the divine oath to Abraham -- since YHWH could swear by no one greater, he swore by himself. The oath guarantees the certainty of what follows.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The divine warrior imagery of YHWH sharpening the flashing sword and the hand gripping the instrument of judgment draws on the standard arsenal of divine warfare in the ancient Near East. Marduk\'s weapons before the battle with Tiamat (Enuma Elish) include flashing weapons; the Baal Cycle describes Baal\'s lightning as his weapon. Deuteronomy appropriates this divine-warrior language for YHWH\'s judgment against the enemies of his people. The double role -- punishing adversaries and those who hate Israel -- is the standard covenant defense: the suzerain protects his vassal.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The arrows drunk with blood and the sword devouring flesh in verse 42 is combat poetry of a type found throughout the ANE. The Ugaritic Baal cycle and the Egyptian battle narratives of Rameses II use similar imagery for divine victory in battle. The imagery of blood-saturated weapons is not gratuitous but functions as a rhetorical reversal: Israel\'s enemies will experience the same devastating defeat they inflicted on Israel.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The closing verse of the Song is itself a site of significant textual divergence. The MT Hebrew is relatively terse; the LXX has an expanded text that adds calls to heavens and divine beings. Romans 15:10 cites a version close to the LXX: Paul quotes it as a proof-text that Gentiles were always intended to rejoice with Israel in YHWH\'s salvation. The verse thus becomes in Paul\'s argument one of four OT witnesses to the inclusion of Gentiles in the messianic community (Rom 15:9-12). The mention of YHWH atoning (<em>wechipper admato ammo</em>, making atonement for the land of his people) is a rare use of the atonement vocabulary outside the sacrificial system -- YHWH\'s own act of vindication constitutes the atonement of the defiled land.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The reference to Joshua as <em>Hoshea ben Nun</em> here is notable because elsewhere in Deuteronomy he is called Joshua (Yehoshua). Numbers 13:16 records that Moses changed the name from Hoshea (salvation) to Yehoshua (YHWH is salvation). The use of the old name here may reflect an archaic tradition or textual preservation. The two names encapsulate the theology of Israelite leadership: Hoshea (human salvation) becomes Yehoshua (YHWH is salvation) -- the human leader\'s effectiveness is derived from and subordinated to divine action.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The framing phrase marks the Song as a completed unit within the larger Deuteronomic speech. The narrative of Moses\'s speaking ministry, interrupted by the Song, is resumed here. Deuteronomy presents Moses as the ultimate teacher-prophet, whose final public act (the Song) is both accusation and promise. The completion of the words (<em>dvarim</em>, both words and deeds) before all Israel is the characteristic Deuteronomic emphasis on the law as a communal possession -- not merely Moses\'s private revelation but the inheritance of the entire assembly.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The instruction to take the warnings to heart and pass them on to children is the Deuteronomic educational mandate applied to the Song. The Shema (6:4-9) had commanded diligent transmission of the law; here the Song -- which is fundamentally a warning about the consequences of covenant failure -- is given the same transmission imperative. In ancient Israelite education, memorized songs and poetry were the primary vehicles for theological instruction: before literacy was widespread, oral traditions in poetic form were the most durable container for doctrinal content.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The declaration that this is not a trivial thing (<em>ki lo dabar req hu mikem</em>, it is not an empty word from you) asserts that the covenant law has existential weight. In wisdom tradition, the opposite of a weighty word is an empty word (<em>davar req</em>) -- advice or teaching that has no purchase on reality. Deuteronomy insists the law is maximally weighty: it is your life (<em>ki hu chayeikhem</em>). This integrative understanding -- that divine instruction is not peripheral to life but constitutive of it -- runs through Paul\'s appropriation of Deuteronomic themes.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The divine commission to Moses to ascend and die on the same day as the Song\'s conclusion creates a literary-structural unity: the Song is Moses\'s last public act, and his death is its immediate sequel. The temporal marker <em>be-etzem ha-yom ha-zeh</em> (on this very day) is used elsewhere in Deuteronomy for events of decisive significance. The commission of death is not a punishment here but the fulfillment of Moses\'s role: he has completed his charge and the moment of transition has arrived.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Mount Nebo (Jebel en-Neba) rises to about 817 meters above the eastern Jordan Valley and on a clear day provides panoramic views across to Judah, the Negev, and the Mediterranean coast. The specific location (Pisgah peak, facing Jericho) is geographically precise and consistent with Num 27:12-14. The location east of the Jordan means Moses will see the Promised Land but die in Transjordan -- the boundary of fulfillment is the boundary of his approach. Nebo is also associated in later tradition with Elijah\'s translation and Moses\'s reappearance at the Transfiguration.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The death of Moses described as being gathered to his ancestors (<em>ve-he\'asef el amekha</em>, be gathered to your people) is the standard OT euphemism for death and burial among one\'s kin. The parallel to Aaron\'s death at Hor (Num 20:23-29) is explicit: both brothers die in the vicinity of the Jordan-Moab region, both are gathered to their people, both deaths mark the boundary of a generation. Even the greatest Israelite does not cross the ultimate boundary on the basis of personal merit -- both leaders who shaped the Exodus generation die outside the land.</p>",
    "51": "<p>The sin at Meribah-kadesh (Num 20:1-13) that disqualified Moses from entering the land is described as unfaithfulness (<em>begaltem bi</em>) against YHWH in the presence of Israel. The precise nature of Moses\'s sin has been debated throughout the tradition: Numbers says he struck the rock twice rather than speaking to it; some traditions emphasize that he spoke as though the miracle were his and Aaron\'s rather than YHWH\'s. Whatever the specific act, the principle is clear: even YHWH\'s most trusted servant is not exempt from the covenant\'s consequences. The water of Meribah (meaning strife/contention) became one of the most discussed episodes in the tradition of Moses\'s character.</p>",
    "52": "<p>The final consequence stated bluntly: Moses will see the land from across the Jordan but will not enter it. The vision from Nebo is the consolation -- YHWH allows Moses to see what was promised but denies him the experience of it. This structure of near-fulfillment-without-full-possession recurs in the OT (Abraham died without possessing the land; David desired to build the temple but was denied). The Epistle to the Hebrews (11:13-16, 39-40) reads this pattern as pointing forward to a better country that the heroes of faith sought, one they would receive only in the company of those who came after them.</p>",
  },
  "33": {
    "1": "<p>Moses is described uniquely here as <em>ish ha-elohim</em> (the man of God) -- a title applied elsewhere in the OT to certain prophets (Elijah, Elisha, Samuel) who operated with special divine authority. The designation marks Moses as more than a lawgiver or leader: he stands in a unique mediating position between YHWH and Israel. The tribal blessing before death is a formal institution in the ancient Near East: patriarchal deathbed blessings (<em>berachot</em>) were understood as prophetic, legally binding, and determinative of the blessed person\'s future. The parallel to Jacob\'s blessing of the twelve tribes (Gen 49) is deliberate: Moses as father-figure of Israel pronounces the destiny of each tribe.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theophanic introduction to the blessing describes YHWH coming from Sinai, rising over Seir (Edom), and shining forth from Paran -- a tripartite geographic description of YHWH\'s approach from the south that corresponds to the route of the wilderness wandering. This southern theophany tradition (also in Judg 5:4-5, Ps 68:7-8, Hab 3:3) is among the oldest strata of Israelite theology. The angelic host (<em>merivvot qodesh</em>, ten thousands of holy ones) accompanying YHWH is the divine council, well-attested in the ANE as the entourage of the storm-god. The connection of angels and the giving of the law is also in Acts 7:53, Gal 3:19, and Heb 2:2.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theological claim that YHWH loves his people and that all his holy ones are in his protective care is the opening frame for the individual tribal blessings. The image of Israel bowing at YHWH\'s feet and receiving instruction from him places the covenant relationship in the posture of attentive discipleship: Israel sits at YHWH\'s feet the way a student sits at a teacher\'s feet (cf. Paul\'s description of his education under Gamaliel in Acts 22:3). The law is received not as a burden imposed from above but as instruction from the one at whose feet the student willingly sits.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Torah as an inheritance (<em>morashah</em>) for the assembly of Jacob is a remarkable claim in the ANE context. Inheritance language in Deuteronomy typically applies to land (the land is Israel\'s <em>nachalah</em>). Here the law is elevated to inheritance status -- it is the most precious thing YHWH bequeaths to his people, more valuable than territory. The Second Temple Jewish tradition developed this elevation of Torah into the central organizing principle of Jewish identity. The Mishnah and Talmud preserve and extend this inheritance, and Paul\'s statement that to Israel belong the covenants and the law (Rom 9:4) reflects its ongoing centrality.</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH\'s kingship over Israel (<em>va-yehi vi-Yeshurun melekh</em>, and he became king in Jeshurun) is the covenant-political claim underlying all of Deuteronomy. YHWH is the true suzerain-king whose law is the covenant constitution. The particular occasion noted -- when the leaders of the people assembled, when the tribes of Israel gathered -- connects the divine kingship to covenant assembly. The tribal assembly was the arena in which YHWH\'s sovereignty was enacted: the covenant ceremony at which Israel renewed its commitments and YHWH renewed his protection. Samuel\'s resistance to the human monarchy (1 Sam 8) draws on this principle: Israel already has a king.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The blessing of Reuben is conspicuously minimal: may he live and not die, though his numbers remain small. The smallness of Reuben is a historical reality -- by the time of the later census lists, Reuben\'s tribe had declined dramatically from its prominence as Jacob\'s firstborn. The historical tradition of Reuben\'s forfeiture of birthright (Gen 49:3-4; 1 Chr 5:1-2) for his offense with Bilhah casts a shadow over his tribal destiny. The blessing is essentially a prayer for bare survival, a contrast to the expansive blessings of Joseph and Asher. Reuben\'s territory east of the Dead Sea was exposed and difficult to defend.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Judah\'s blessing is a prayer for military success and territorial unity: bring him to his people, let his own hands be sufficient, and help him against his foes. The phrase <em>shema YHWH qol yehudah</em> (hear, YHWH, the voice of Judah) is unusual -- why does Judah\'s voice need to be heard? Some interpreters read this as a prayer for Judah\'s voice to be heard among the tribes (political leadership) or in the assembly. The prayer that YHWH\'s hands be sufficient for him connects Judah\'s military prowess to divine assistance. The subsequent centrality of Judah (the tribe of David and the messianic line) makes this simple blessing retrospectively significant.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Urim and Thummim were the oracular lots kept in the priest\'s breastpiece (Exod 28:30; Lev 8:8; Num 27:21) and used to determine divine will in specific decisions. Their precise mechanism is unknown -- the words may mean light/perfection or right/left -- but they were understood as a reliable binary oracle that gave yes/no answers to specific questions put to YHWH. The reference to Massah and Meribah in the Levi blessing connects the priestly office to the episode of testing in the wilderness (Exod 17:7; Num 20:13). YHWH tested Levi at Massah and contended with him at Meribah -- the testing proved the tribe faithful.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The priestly requirement to put loyalty to YHWH above family ties refers to the episode of Levi\'s zeal at Sinai (Exod 32:25-29), where the Levites executed those who had participated in the golden-calf apostasy, even killing family members. The Levitical self-denial here is a specific act of covenant loyalty that YHWH endorsed as the basis for priestly service: only those who can subordinate natural affections to covenant obligation are fit to mediate between YHWH and the people. This is the demanding side of priestly vocation -- the priest must be more loyal to the sanctuary than to his own household (cf. Ezek 44:25-27 on priestly mourning restrictions).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The dual functions of the Levites -- teaching the law and performing the sacrificial cult -- represent the two dimensions of the priestly office. The teaching function (<em>yorekha mishpatekha le-Yaakov</em>, they will teach your ordinances to Jacob) was foundational in the pre-monarchic period when priests served as the primary repositories and transmitters of the covenant law. The gradual erosion of this teaching function and the substitution of other teachers (prophets, scribes, sages) is a major feature of the Second Temple period. Ezra\'s combination of priest and scribe represents an attempt to recover this original Levitical teaching role.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The blessing of Levi\'s resources and the prayer to shatter his enemies reflects the political vulnerability of a tribe without territorial inheritance. The Levites were dispersed through 48 cities among the other tribes and economically dependent on the sacrificial system and the good will of the surrounding tribal communities. In practice, Levites were sometimes exploited (Judg 17-18, the Levite hired as a household priest) and displaced (2 Kgs 23:8-9, the provincial Levites unable to serve at Jerusalem after Josiah\'s centralization). The prayer for YHWH\'s blessing of their resources acknowledges this structural vulnerability.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Benjamin\'s blessing as <em>yedid YHWH</em> (the beloved of the LORD) who rests in safety on YHWH\'s shoulders is widely connected to Jerusalem\'s location in Benjamin\'s territory. The permanent location of YHWH\'s sanctuary within the territory of the beloved tribe is a fulfillment of this blessing. The image of resting between YHWH\'s shoulders uses the protective-warrior imagery of the divine carrier also present in 32:11 (the eagle carrying its young) and 33:27 (the everlasting arms). Benjamin is the small tribe that lives under the immediate protection of the divine patron.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Joseph\'s blessing is the most elaborate in the chapter, reflecting the dominant position of the Joseph tribes (Ephraim and Manasseh) in the northern kingdom. The catalog of blessings -- dew from above, springs from below, sun, moon, mountain produce, age-old hills -- covers the full range of agricultural benefactors in ancient Israel. The <em>meged</em> (best/choicest) applied to each source is the vocabulary of firstfruits and tithes -- everything is best. The theological claim is that Joseph\'s land possesses the maximum blessing in every domain: this is the vocabulary of covenant fullness.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The seasonal structure of the blessing in verses 14-15 moves through the full agricultural cycle: from the sun-ripened crops of summer to the harvest of each season to the riches of the mountains. In agricultural Palestine, the blessing of rain and dew at the right time was YHWH\'s gift that no human management could secure. The reference to each <em>yerachim</em> (lunar months/seasons) reflects the agricultural calendar that structured Israelite life -- three pilgrimage festivals (Passover, Weeks, Tabernacles) corresponded to the three harvest seasons (barley, wheat, fruit). Joseph\'s blessing covers all of them.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The <em>harerei qedem</em> (ancient mountains) and <em>givot olam</em> (everlasting hills) describe the geological timescale of blessing: the mineral and agricultural wealth of the highlands goes back to creation. This is a contrast to Baal\'s seasonal fertility gifts (which required annual renewal through cultic ritual) -- YHWH\'s provision is built into the permanent structure of creation. The age of the mountains is a sign of the permanence of YHWH\'s covenant blessing: it does not need to be renewed annually through ritual but is embedded in the created order itself.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The burning bush reference (<em>shokeni sneh</em>, the favor of him who dwelt in the thornbush) connects Joseph\'s blessing to the Exodus theophany -- the foundational moment when YHWH revealed himself to Moses as the God of the ancestors (Exod 3:1-6). The dwelling (<em>shakhan</em>) of YHWH in the burning bush uses the same root as the Shekinah glory -- YHWH\'s presence that dwelt in the wilderness tabernacle and eventually in the Jerusalem temple. The prayer that the favor of the Exodus God rest on Joseph connects the tribal blessing to the entire redemptive history that created the covenant people.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Joseph\'s bull/wild-ox imagery draws on ANE royal iconography. The bull was the symbol of strength and fertility in Canaanite religion (El the bull-god of Ugarit) and of royal power in Mesopotamian and Egyptian art. The wild ox (<em>reem</em>) was a symbol of untamed power -- probably the aurochs, which was extinct in Palestine by the Roman period but attested in Bronze Age hunting reliefs. The horns pushing nations to the ends of the earth is the expansionist empire metaphor of the Joseph tribes, which dominated the northern kingdom from the time of Joshua through the monarchy.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The pairing of Zebulun (who ventures abroad) and Issachar (who dwells in tents) reflects the traditional division of economic roles that the two neighboring tribes were understood to have. Issachar occupied the fertile Jezreel Valley (the most productive agricultural land in Palestine) while Zebulun\'s territory extended toward the sea. The rabbinic tradition developed this complementarity: Zebulun engaged in trade and supported Issachar in Torah study -- the Issachar-Zebulun partnership became a model for supporting scholars through commercial patronage.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The summons of nations to the mountain for sacrifice and the drawing of wealth from the seas and sand represent the universal scope of YHWH\'s blessing mediated through the northern tribes. Zebulun\'s access to Mediterranean trade routes and the Jezreel Valley\'s agricultural surplus made these tribes wealthy in the monarchy period. The phrase <em>shefunei temunei chol</em> (treasures hidden in the sand) may refer to the purple dye from the murex snail found on the beaches of the Phoenician coast (Zebulun\'s territory bordered Phoenicia), which was one of the most valuable commercial commodities in the ancient world.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gad\'s blessing as the enlarged one and the lion-tearer reflects the military character of this tribe\'s territory: east of the Jordan in the Gilead, Gad faced constant pressure from Moab, Ammon, and Aramean kingdoms. The lion imagery recurs in the tribal blessings (Judah as lion cub in Gen 49:9; Dan as lion\'s cub in v.22) and reflects the warrior function of the tribe. The description of Gad as one who chooses the best portion for himself suggests that Gad\'s territory in the Gilead, though east of the Jordan and apparently disadvantaged, was in fact some of the richest pastoral land in the region.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The reference to Gad\'s leader\'s portion being kept there and to Gad marching with the leaders of the people reflects the tradition of Gad\'s tribal loyalty in the conquest. The Gadites, along with Reuben and half Manasseh, had been granted territory east of the Jordan on the condition that their fighting men would cross the Jordan with the other tribes to help in the conquest (Num 32:16-32; Josh 1:12-18). The law of YHWH and his ordinances with Israel -- the commitment of the eastern tribes to the common covenant cause -- is the theological ground for Gad\'s territorial claim.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Dan is compared to a lion\'s cub (<em>gur aryeh</em>) that springs out of Bashan. The Bashan was the fertile highland plateau east of the Sea of Galilee, famous for its cattle and oak forests (Ps 22:12; Amos 4:1). Dan\'s original tribal territory was in the southwest near the coastal plain (Judg 13-16: Samson\'s exploits were in Danite territory), but the tribe later migrated northward to the city of Laish (Judg 18) near the sources of the Jordan in the far north, near Bashan. The blessing may anticipate or reflect this northern migration.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Naphtali\'s blessing as <em>seba ratzon</em> (overflowing with favor) and <em>male birkat YHWH</em> (full of the LORD\'s blessing) connects to the territory around the Sea of Galilee and the fertile Upper Galilee. Isaiah\'s prophecy about Zebulun and Naphtali seeing a great light (Isa 9:1-2) was fulfilled in the Gospel narratives by Jesus\'s ministry in Galilee (Matt 4:13-16). The region that received the most minimal blessing in the military-political history of Israel became the epicenter of the messianic ministry.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Asher\'s blessing as the most blessed and the favorite of his brothers reflects the tribe\'s territory on the fertile coastal plain of northern Canaan. The Asherite coast produced olive oil in quantities sufficient for export -- the reference to bathing the foot in oil is hyperbolic but grounded in the reality of Asher\'s olive culture. The archaeological evidence for large-scale olive oil production in the Galilean hills confirms the agricultural basis of this blessing. Asher\'s territory also included some of the wealthiest Phoenician port cities.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Iron and bronze bolts (<em>barzel vi-nechoshet minale ekha</em>) suggest military defense infrastructure -- the bolts of a well-fortified city. The prayer that Asher\'s strength would match the length of days is a longevity and resilience blessing appropriate to a tribe on the vulnerable northern frontier of Israel\'s territory. The Asherite territory bordered the Phoenician coast and was exposed to pressure from Phoenician city-states to the west and Aramean kingdoms to the north. The military strength blessing acknowledges this exposed position while expressing confidence in divine provision.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The closing doxology of verses 26-29 returns to the theophanic imagery of the introduction. <em>Yeshurun</em> again designates Israel as the ideal covenant people who receive the blessing of the one who rides the heavens (<em>rokeb shamayim</em>). The divine warrior riding through the heavens is one of the oldest Israelite theological images, paralleled closely in the Ugaritic texts describing Baal riding the clouds. Deuteronomy appropriates this imagery for YHWH: the God of Israel is the true storm-rider and cloud-rider whose sovereignty extends from the heavenly heights to the eternal foundations beneath (v.27).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The image of YHWH as the eternal refuge (<em>me-onah elohei qedem</em>, the eternal God is your dwelling) and of the everlasting arms underneath Israel is one of the most beloved images of divine protection in the OT. The spatial metaphor is three-dimensional: above is the God who rides the heavens (v.26); below are the everlasting arms that support and carry. The combination means Israel is surrounded in every direction -- above, below, and beside -- by the divine presence. The expulsion of the enemy and the promise of safe dwelling continues the divine-warrior theme: YHWH fights and his people rest in security.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Israel dwelling in safety (<em>va-yishkon yisrael betach badad</em>, Israel dwelt in security, alone) is the covenant peace that results from YHWH\'s protection. The aloneness (<em>badad</em>) is not isolation but distinctiveness: Israel\'s security does not depend on alliances with other nations but on its covenant relationship with YHWH alone. This theological principle is repeatedly violated in the monarchy period as Israel sought security through diplomatic alliances (Isa 30:1-5 against the Egyptian alliance; Hos 7:11 against running to Egypt and Assyria). The grain and new wine and the dew-dropping sky summarize the covenant blessings of Deuteronomy 28:1-14.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The closing question <em>ashrekha Yisrael mi kamokha</em> (blessed are you, O Israel -- who is like you?) echoes the divine uniqueness formula used of YHWH himself (<em>mi chamokha ba-elim YHWH</em>, Exod 15:11: who is like you among the gods, YHWH?). Israel\'s uniqueness is derivative from YHWH\'s uniqueness: a people so blessed because their God is uniquely powerful. The three roles -- YHWH as help, shield, and sword -- constitute a complete military patron. The treading down of the high places of enemies is the conquest imagery that concludes the blessing collection: the blessed life of the tribes is grounded in the military success that YHWH guarantees.</p>",
  },
  "34": {
    "1": "<p>Mount Nebo (Jebel en-Neba) rises to about 817 meters above the eastern Jordan Valley and on a clear day provides panoramic views across to Judah, the Negev, and the Mediterranean coast. The specific location (Pisgah peak, facing Jericho) is geographically precise and consistent with Num 27:12-14. The panoramic vision of the entire land before Moses enters it is theologically structured: YHWH shows Moses the fulfillment of the promise he cannot personally receive. The vision is both gift and grief -- the near-fulfillment-without-possession that characterizes so many OT figures and that Hebrews 11 reads as pointing forward to a better country.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The geographic catalog in verses 1-3 is structured to cover the entire land promised to Israel: from the northernmost point (Dan and Naphtali) to the Negev in the south, from the Jordan Valley in the east to the Mediterranean in the west. The panoramic sweep covers every tribal allotment and every significant region. The list is not merely topographic but theological: YHWH is showing Moses the full extent of the promise made to Abraham (Gen 15:18-21). The mention of Ephraim and Manasseh (Joseph\'s sons) fills in the central highlands; the mention of Judah to the sea covers the southwest.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Negev (the dry south), the Jordan Valley (the <em>kikkar</em>, the plain/circle), the date-palm city of Jericho (<em>ir ha-temarim</em>) as far as Zoar completes the southern and eastern survey. Jericho was known in antiquity for its date palms -- Josephus and Roman-era writers describe extensive palm groves. Zoar was one of the five cities of the plain (Gen 13:10; 14:2) associated with Sodom and Gomorrah; Lot fled there when the cities were destroyed (Gen 19:22-23). The citation of Sodom-area geography at the end of the survey recalls the covenant judgment narrated in Genesis and frames the land as a place of both blessing and potential judgment.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The divine speech at Nebo recalls the threefold patriarchal promise: the land was sworn to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. The specific formula is the core covenant commitment that drives the entire Pentateuchal narrative. Moses has embodied the covenant\'s mediation but is not the covenant\'s beneficiary: he dies on the threshold of the promise, having seen but not possessed. Hebrews 11:13-16 reads this pattern as pointing to the patriarchs and Moses seeking a better, heavenly country. The verb <em>he\'eti</em> (I have let you see it) emphasizes divine gift even in the moment of denial.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Moses is described at his death as <em>eved YHWH</em> (servant of the LORD), the title that defines his identity throughout the Torah (Exod 14:31; Num 12:7-8; Josh 1:1-2, 7, 13). In the ancient Near East, the designation of a royal official as servant of the king was an honorific indicating intimate access and trusted status; applied to Moses, it carries the same weight. The phrase <em>al pi YHWH</em> (by the mouth/word of the LORD) describing his death is unique -- it suggests not merely that his death was commanded but that it occurred in direct obedience to divine word, perhaps indicating a peaceful death by divine will rather than by illness or violence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The divine burial of Moses in an unknown grave is unique in scripture. The anonymity of the burial site has been interpreted as protection against the veneration of Moses\'s tomb, which in the ancient Near East would have become a pilgrimage site and potentially an object of cult. The tradition of the unknown grave preserved Israel from the tomb-worship that surrounded figures like the Egyptian pharaohs. The brief notice in Jude 9 about Michael and the devil disputing over Moses\'s body may reflect an early Jewish tradition explaining the anonymity of the grave as the result of divine intervention to prevent its use as a cult site.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Moses\'s age (120 years) and the report that his eyesight was not dimmed and his vigor not fled is presented as a miracle of sustained vitality. In the ancient world, 120 years was considered the maximum possible human lifespan (the Sumerian king lists sometimes cite 120 years as a legendary maximum). Moses\'s undimmed eye contrasts with Isaac (Gen 27:1) and Jacob (Gen 48:10) whose eyesight failed in old age. Moses dies at the full height of his powers, not worn out, which emphasizes that his death is not natural deterioration but divine calling home -- YHWH\'s timing, not the body\'s failure.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The thirty-day mourning period for Moses corresponds to the mourning for Aaron (Num 20:29) and is the formal period of national grief for Israel\'s leaders. In ancient Israel, mourning rituals included tearing garments, wearing sackcloth, putting dust on the head, fasting, and lamentation. The public mourning for a leader was both an expression of communal grief and a ritual acknowledgment of political succession -- until the mourning was complete, the transition to the next leader was not formally sealed. The conclusion of the mourning period here immediately precedes Joshua\'s accession as the narrative\'s next major move.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Joshua\'s investiture through Moses\'s laying on of hands (<em>semicha</em>) transmitted the spirit of wisdom and established the legal succession of prophetic-leadership authority. The laying on of hands (<em>semekh et yadav alav</em>, he laid his hands on him) was used in the OT for various acts of identification and transmission: sacrificial offerings (Lev 1:4), blessing (Gen 48:14), consecration of Levites (Num 8:10), and ordination of leaders (Num 27:18-23). The rabbis developed the <em>semicha</em> tradition as the formal chain of rabbinic ordination going back to Moses; this verse is the foundational text for that unbroken chain of transmitted authority.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The epitaph focuses on Moses\'s direct personal knowledge of YHWH (<em>asher yedo YHWH panim el panim</em>, whom YHWH knew face to face) as the basis for his unparalleled prophetic status. This echoes Num 12:6-8, where YHWH distinguishes Moses from all other prophets: while others receive visions and dreams, Moses speaks with YHWH mouth to mouth, clearly, not in riddles, and he sees the form of YHWH. The face-to-face language is the strongest possible statement of prophetic intimacy. The anticipation of a future prophet like Moses (18:15) -- also face-to-face, also speaking YHWH\'s words directly -- shapes the entire prophetic tradition that follows and finds its fulfillment in Christ (Acts 3:22; 7:37).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The closing verse of the Torah celebrates the <em>yad chazaqah</em> (strong hand) and <em>mora gadol</em> (great terror) Moses displayed before all Israel as acts of YHWH\'s power mediated through him. The specific reference to the signs and wonders in Egypt (v.11) and the awesome deeds before all Israel (v.12) frames Moses\'s entire ministry in terms of visible, communal, historical demonstration of YHWH\'s power. The Torah ends not with a law code or a doctrinal statement but with the memory of a man through whom YHWH acted visibly in history. The implication: the covenant law Israel has received is not an abstract ethical code but the gift of the God who demonstrated his power and character through Moses\'s ministry.</p>",
  },
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'deuteronomy')
    merge_comm(existing, DEUTERONOMY)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'deuteronomy', existing)
    print('Deuteronomy 32-34 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
